Coincidence between LCP.
255 alpha-alpha and 37 alpha-triton coincidences.
In the decay of Be-8 from g.s. of half-life 0.07 fs,
Q-value=0.092 MeV lead to narrow angular correlation
between the two alpha`s. Simulating the kinematics has
yielded maximum opening angle 8deg at average kinetic
energy of Be-8. Since the smallest angle for detection
of an alpha pair in neighboring  detectors is 16deg, so
in the Cf experiment only the decay from excited states
of Be-8 can contribute to the observed enhancement at
angles <60deg. Thus, the measured pseudo alpha-alpha QF
has to be attributed to the sequential decay of short-
lived 2+ first excited state in Be-8 at E*=3.04 MeV
(T1/2=3.E-22 s; Q=3.13 MeV). Simulation calculations
have yielded a significantly broader distribution of
opening angles which matches with high probability the
angular range covered by the setup. Similar observation
holds for the decay of Li-7* from the 2nd excited state
Contributions from higher-lying states than quoted
can be safely ruled out for Be-8, while for Li-7 3rd
excited state at E*=6.68 MeV may be responsible for an
estimated 10% of the total alpha-triton decay observed.
Sequential QF with intermediate Li-7 state
resulting in pair alpha-triton.
Sequential QF with intermediate Be-8 state
resulting in pair alpha-alpha.
Yields were determined for full energy distribution by
extrapolating the angular distribution from data at
opening angles >60deg to the full angular range.
Yield of Be-8 formed in g.s. had determined indirectly
using measured E-rest spectrum and data of REL-REFs;
average alpha energy was assumed to be 10.MeV with
FWHM 10.MeV in fitting routine.
